dging the residue of magic’s colonial origins doesn’t require us to dispense with it. Rather, through this radical reassessment of classic anthropological ideas, Magic’s Reason develops a new perspective on the promise and peril of cross-cultural comparison.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMagicxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAlgeria.  aFrance.  aanalogy.  aanthropology.  aconjuring.  aethnography.  aillusionism.  amagic.  aresearch methods.  aspiritualism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226518718423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226518718.jpg  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles